text:
Might be a pretty good indicator where IOG‚Äôs focus is these days. 

#Cardano community, be weary of the ‚Äòdevelopment contract‚Äô that will certainly be submitted by IOG to be paid for out of our treasury. 

We must ensure there is a clear understanding of where the companies focuses and the manpower/funds allocated from the Cardano treasury must be used in FULL for Cardano development. It may not be a bad idea for us as a chain to seek more than one development contract or better yet to ensure the pending contract will have IOG training and additional company/team to take on development and give us more options. 

We cannot be held hostage by any of these existing entities, and there is still much clarification to be made regarding who has been responsible for certain failures to the community. 

It is my goal to ensure that Cardano can be steered towards a future outside of the hands of any one team, entity, or class. Making the governance process more accessible and doing my utmost to prevent the traditional money drainers from our ecosystem or ANYONE who feels that bureaucratic classes or roles here in Cardano deserve their living and travel expenses paid out of the pocket of our ecosystem is firmly held to account and limited in scope of the funds they should have access to. 

Austerity is the key. This is OUR dowry, and we‚Äôve already seen how some teams like @3utxoCapital with outsized representation and access to our funding mechanisms is moving to take huge sums from our treasury out the gate. Players like @adamKDean were involved there. And the work so far from some of those founding members of @3utxoCapital run there businesses here on chain with heavy reliance on our funding mechanisms and less than stellar deliverables. 

These people with access to our top level leadership and the greatest chances at the treasury are often NOT our friends. They will often times NOT be honest or transparent. Many have been funded with large sums of our tx fees and yet do not care to abide by the same ethos we expect them to uphold. 

I feel at this point it‚Äôs been made quite clear how many takers have been able to operate so long in the past, but the question remains ‚ÄúWhat are we gonna do about it?‚Äù 

I‚Äôve made sure to draw very clear lines in the sand within my own work here. I will not participate in business with people who are not holding Cardano and this community in the highest regard, or are moving in ethically immoral manners. 

Unfortunately there are many ‚Äòleaders‚Äô here in this space that have already shown us their true colors. And their lack of concern for the wider community. 

$FIGHT back, go vote. üó≥Ô∏è Join @IntersectMBO and participate in the upcoming committee elections. We absolutely must act now as a community to ensure the folks in these seats are people that align with our core values and can commit to helping resolve some of these problems and challenges that face us. 

Catalyst is now only needing 25 $ADA to vote. Use it! Vote for the projects building for the future with real plans. Not dreams depending on consistent catalyst funds.

text:
Cardano Founder Confirms IOG Working on Protocol to Surpass Solana‚Äôs Speed...

Cardano founder  @IOHK_Charles  says IOG is ramping up efforts to improve Cardano‚Äôs speed, aiming to outpace competitors like Solana.

In a recent community poll by  @RichardMcCrackn, a #Cardano community figure associated with the stake pool operator (SPO) Digital Fortress, members were asked to choose between two proposals. In the hypothetical scenario, these proposals would enhance the network using a budget of 20 million ADA every month.

The choices were between building a Rust-based node for 11 million $ADA or implementing the Leios protocol for 12 million ADA. Of the 1,798 participants, 56% voted in favor of the Leios proposal, while only 7% supported the Rust node option.

Cardano Founder Responds...

In response to the poll, Charles Hoskinson, the founder of Cardano, stressed the potential benefits of the Leios protocol. He highlighted that the Rust node would not bring any significant new features to users.

In contrast, the Leios protocol provides a chance to enhance Cardano‚Äôs transaction throughput, making it faster than Solana without sacrificing its decentralization.

Solana with its high-speed transaction processing has been a strong competitor in the space. However, some argue that its speed comes at the cost of decentralization, an area where Cardano aims to maintain a competitive edge. Solana has also faced issues with outages.

Leios Aims to Boost Transaction Speed...

The Ouroboros Leios protocol looks to surpass this speed level while preserving Cardano‚Äôs decentralization. This protocol separates the validation of transactions from the creation of new blocks, introducing ‚Äúinput endorsers,‚Äù a concept that could boost transaction speeds.

Despite Leios‚Äô promising nature, one community member expressed concern, noting that the protocol should have been a priority years ago. He pointed out that an open-sourced paper alone isn‚Äôt enough unless the technology is actively built and implemented.

Hoskinson addressed these concerns, explaining that a dedicated team, led by  @InputOutputHK  (IOG), is already working on the design of the Leios protocol. The team‚Äôs efforts will expand in Q4 2024 after completing work on the Peras Cardano Improvement Proposal (CIP).

Meanwhile,  @Cerkoryn, a Cardano dRep, asked whether there would be opportunities for community builders to participate in the Leios prototyping team. He noted the importance of diversifying development efforts beyond IOG to ensure a decentralized approach to core development.

Hoskinson responded affirmatively, stating that the aim is to involve third-party developers through a request-for-proposal (RFP) process, similar to how Cardano handled the development of the Genesis protocol with Tweag and the upcoming Peras.

Notably, Hoskinson confirmed that due to how complex the Leios protocol is, it would require more than a dozen firms to be involved in its full implementation. The Rust node proposal, while receiving less support, is still a crucial part of Cardano‚Äôs development. Rust is known for being fast, secure, and lightweight... 

Author : Sam Wisdom Raphael.

@Cardano

text:
Let's break down how hardware wallets work. Once you understand this, you'll see that you can safely use multiple #Cardano light wallets.

This enables you to perform governance operations, such as delegating $ADA to a DRep.

When you set up a hardware wallet, it generates a recovery seed (passphrase), which is a list of 12 to 24 words. 

This seed is crucial as it can be used to recover your wallet if the device is lost or damaged. You can use any wallet to restore your account, not the one you used before.

From this seed, a master private key is derived. This master private key is the root from which all other keys are generated.

Using the master private key, a master public key is derived. This public key can be used to generate multiple public addresses to receive funds.

From this master private key, multiple private keys are derived for different blockchains like #Bitcoin, #Ethereum, Cardano, etc. 

This is done using specific derivation paths defined by various standards. 

From these blockchain-specific private keys, multiple public keys are derived. These public keys can be exported to light wallets.

Importing the public key into a wallet is a secure process. Even if someone obtains your public key, they can only view your account details, not steal your assets.

Public keys allow light wallets to derive addresses thus building transactions.

However, a light wallet with an imported public key cannot sign transactions. To do so, the private key stored in the hardware wallet must be used.

Note that the same transaction can be constructed in any Cardano wallet.

A hardware wallet is a type of cold wallet. Being a cold wallet means it is offline and not connected to the internet, making it much harder for hackers to access.

When you use a light wallet with a hardware wallet like Trezor or Ledger, you typically import the public key (or an extended public key) from the hardware wallet. 

This allows the light wallet to generate addresses and view your balance and transaction history without needing access to your private keys.

When you need to sign a transaction, the light wallet sends the transaction details to the hardware wallet. 

The hardware wallet then signs the transaction internally and sends the signed transaction back to the light wallet, which broadcasts it to the network. 

Typically to a full node operated by the light wallet team.

This setup ensures that your private keys never leave the hardware wallet, maintaining a high level of security. 

The user only handles the seed (passphrase) once during the initial setup of the hardware wallet. After that, there's no need to interact with it again.

You can use multiple Cardano wallets, including Daedalus (a full node wallet), simultaneously with a hardware wallet. 

This allows you to leverage the unique features of each wallet. For example, one wallet might better display NFTs, while another enables you to perform governance transactions like DRep registration or delegation.

If your Cardano wallet doesn't support governance operations, you can safely import the public key from one hardware wallet to another. 

The new wallet will either support governance operations internally or allow you to connect to GovTools.

If you don't use a hardware wallet, you likely wrote down the seed on paper when setting up a light wallet.

In that case, you would need to manually enter the seed into another wallet using the restore wallet function. 

However, this can be !risky!, as malicious software like keyloggers can capture the seed and pass it to a hacker. 

I don't recommend doing this unless you are confident in your ability to do it safely.

text:
Many people don't delegate $ADA to DReps because their wallet doesn't support it.

There's a simple solution: import your passphrase into another light wallet.

Wallets are simply a blockchain interface. It doesn't matter which #Cardano wallet you use to sign a transaction or delegate to a DRep.

You can use multiple wallets simultaneously, meaning the same passphrase can be used across different wallets. Sometimes it's even handy.

For hardware wallets, this process is completely safe, although caution is advised when entering the passphrase manually.

You can install a wallet that supports governance actions, or with which you can connect to GovTools.

On the Intersect website, you can find an overview of wallets that support governance.

text:
A recent post criticized the @IntersectMBO Governance Parameters Working Group in setting the Governance Deposit fee.

The charge: This "absurd protocol parameter" is keeping #Cardano users from submitting Governance Actions.

My plea: Guilty as charged.

Let's talk about why this is necessary!

If you're a Cardano enthusiast you are probably here because you recognize that every system has trade-offs.  Cardano has developed at a slow and steady pace because Security, Scalability, and Decentralization (not to mention speed!) can't all be tackled at the same time.

Governance is no different.  With the implementation of CIP-1694 we are replacing a federated system of governance with a community system of governance.

The old system: IOG, Cardano Foundation, and Emurgo were responsible for the development roadmap and network parameters.  The SPOs got to decide whether or not to implement these proposed upgrades on the nodes that they ran. Ada holders selected the SPOs.

This was a relatively simple system where the three Genesis entities could have their engineers in constant communication via Slack channels and the SPOs would keep up with each other and the developers on Discord and through monthly calls.

The new system: Ada Holders control the development roadmap and network parameters through strategic planning and treasury allocation by their Delegate Representatives. SPOs have a say in hard forks, security parameters, and constitutional matters. A Constitutional Committee ensures that any Governance Actions proposed are in line with a published Constitution that outlines the rights of Ada holders and aspirations of the Cardano network.

This is a pretty complex system that already involves dozens of people (when it isn't even fully implemented) and will eventually bring thousands or perhaps millions of people into the decision-making process.

In order for any parameter to be changed, any withdrawal be made from the treasury, or any update be made to the Cardano node software, a Governance Action must be proposed.  The Governance Action Proposal needs to be examined by DReps, Constitutional Committee Members, and perhaps SPOs to make sure it is acceptable, and then those individuals need to vote YES in a high enough threshold to approve it.

The specific item being challenged is that when a Governance Action is proposed, at least 100,000 ADA must be deposited with it, to be held for 6 epochs (30 days) to indicate the seriousness of the proposer.  This number was arrived at from discussion between the Governance Parameters Working Group (who initially suggested 50,000 ADA) and the full Parameters Committee, which had many technical experts that wanted to set the deposit set even higher.

Keep in mind, we need to have a reasonable amount of Governance Action Proposals being considered at any given time.  If there are no Governance Action Proposals to consider, we essentially have a dead chain and no future.  If we have too many Governance Action Proposals, we won't be able to give them all a fair consideration because there will be too many to read.

So the question is - how do we decide who gets to make Governance Action Proposals?

One thing we can do is look at how other DAOs handle this situation.  Uniswap is currently the most valuable DAO in the world with a reported market cap of $6.8 Billion USD.  Holders of UNI tokens govern this platform through community votes on Governance Action Proposals.

However, in order for a Governance Action Proposal to come up for vote it must first be socialized in the Uniswap Governance Forums (which appears to just be an implementation of the open-source Discourse software), put up for a Temperature Check via Off-chain Snapshot vote, and then if the Temp Check meets threshold it can be proposed on-chain without being vetoed.

Should Cardano do this?  Who do you trust to run the Discussion Forum?  Who will run the Temp Check tool?  Will that group remain uncorrupted?

Oh, and I forgot to mention... you must hold or be delegated at least 2.5 Million UNI tokens ($16 Million USD) to propose a Uniswap Governance Action.

Let's go in the opposite direction... the radical populist position that my friend Keep in is more in favor of üòâ.  What if we were to only require 250 ADA for a Governance Action Deposit?

Well, let's just say I've seen the sh*tcoins that you absolute degens pump out!  If Uncle Charlie posts a picture of a roast beef sandwich there's going to be a BBQWTF coin the next day, for Cardano Pete's Sake...

The way our Voltaire Governance system is set up, each governance member has to actively decide to vote YES on an action or it is effectively a NO vote.  Again, this means that we want each Governance Action Proposal to be considered on its merits.

If DReps are bombarded by too many Governance Actions to consider, will we have broad participation?  There is an active question in Cardano right now about whether DReps should be considered "full time" or "part time" governance actors.  Think about your own, traiditional, governments.  Do you feel that full time or part time legislators serve you better?  Or if you vote on ballot initiatives yourself, are you always informed about all of the proposals listed?

I see this as an even bigger problem for the Constitutional Committee.  The job of the CC is not to decide whether an action is "good" or "bad" but rather whether or not it is permitted by the Cardano Constitution.  If the CC doesn't have time to examine each Governance Action Proposal, they are effectively casting a "No" vote by not voting... or worse, making a hasty decision about constitutionality.

But, let's say that we allow for the radical populist submission of Governance Action Proposals anyways.  How can we handle the situation?  Many have proposed proposal viewing software to "filter out the Spam" but again, I ask you, who do you trust to build this software?  Who do you trust to tune the filters and determine what is Spam?  How will we keep this from being a faux democracy where we just ignore certain voices because it's easy to tune them out with centralized control of the methods of communication?

Ultimately, that is why I believe that rate limiting Governance Action Proposals is essential and the best way of doing it is by having a high enough amount of ADA required for deposit.  We will undoubtedly be lowering this number over time, especially if Ada rises in terms of USD price!  But let's get past Chang+1 and full implementation of the governance system so we can do assessment on what that is.

text:
The implementation of Ouroboros Leios and Peras will enhance throughput and accelerate settlement times for the Nakamoto consensus.

This will enable #Cardano to handle hundreds to thousands of transactions with a finality time of just 2 minutes, all while preserving the network's robustness and decentralization.

Let me describe the inefficiency of the first-generation Nakamoto consensus.

A blockchain is a linear data structure where each new block builds on the previous one. The first generation of the Nakamoto consensus follows this linear, sequential approach. 

Currently, both Cardano and #Bitcoin operate similarly.

The Nakamoto consensus is inefficient as it doesn't fully utilize available computing resources and bandwidth. 

Network activity peaks when a new block is created and propagated, requiring all nodes to validate it through the same computation. 

During the intervals between block production, resources remain underutilized.

In the image, red slots represent periods of increased activity, while white slots indicate unused resources. 

While waiting for another block, these resources are primarily used for pre-validating transactions that are added to the mem-pool.

Transactions are not instantly finalized when added to a new block. Even a newly appended block does not guarantee finality. 

Blockchain forks can occur, leading to two competing chains. 

One of them becomes part of the blockchain history and the second one is discarded (orphaned). 

True finality is achieved only after several subsequent blocks are added. Users gauge this finality by the number of confirmations‚Äîblocks added after a block with their transactions. Consequently, the Nakamoto consensus has a relatively long settlement time.

Ouroboros Peras will enable a sufficient number of nodes (and their respective stakes) to agree on the ledger's state through voting. 

This will significantly reduce transaction finality time and lower the risk of large rollbacks after just a few blocks.

A randomly selected committee of SPOs will vote for the block at a fixed depth from their current best chain tip within a given period, increasing the weight of blocks that a majority of SPOs agree upon. 

This method, known as stake-based voting, allows a greater number of nodes to approve blocks, including previous ones, more quickly.

The chain selection process will be based on the chain's weight rather than its length, meaning nodes will consider votes (and certificates) instead of the number of blocks. 

The heaviest chain will prevail over the longer one.

Votes will be broadcast to all nodes across the network. If a node observes a quorum of votes for the same block, it can issue a certificate that increases the block's weight. 

Certificates will also be disseminated across the network on demand to nodes that lack equivalent votes.

If the block producer has a new certificate available, it will insert it into the block, propagating the certificate throughout the network.

Yellow blocks represent blocks that nodes vote on. Blue blocks contain certificates.

Users will have absolute certainty about transaction finality within 2 minutes, compared to the current 12 hours (2160 blocks).

Ouroboros Leios is designed to achieve near-optimal throughput, handling an exceptionally high volume of transactions and pushing the network's capacity to its limits within existing constraints.

Every blockchain network has a maximum number of transactions it can process, known as capacity. 

This is the system's peak ability to manage workload or perform tasks under ideal conditions, influenced by factors like network bandwidth, available computational power, and system design.

The network's actual capacity is often significantly lower than its theoretically usable capacity in terms of resources.

Throughput is the actual number of transactions processed in a given time frame. 

It measures real-world performance, indicating how many transactions are confirmed and recorded on the blockchain, often expressed as transactions per second (TPS). 

While capacity represents theoretical potential, throughput reflects practical achievement.

The first generation of the Nakamoto consensus doesn't effectively utilize available resources. 

Ouroboros Leios addresses this by introducing three types of blocks: 

- Input Blocks (data carriers containing transactions) 
- Endorsement Blocks (reference Input Blocks)
- Ranking Blocks (reference Endorsement Blocks)

Endorsement Blocks can reference multiple Input Blocks. Nodes validate blocks and vote on their readiness for inclusion in the blockchain through Ranking Blocks. 

The voting result is a certificate that the blocks carry with them. These certificates are verified when inserted into the blockchain.

Stake-based voting, similar to Ouroboros Peras, can be used for voting on Endorsement Blocks.

Multiple Input Blocks can be minted within a single second and are subsequently referenced by Endorsement Blocks. 

Parallelization is essential for enhancing transaction processing efficiency. 

By decoupling Input and Endorsement Blocks from Ranking Blocks, their processing can leverage parallelization, avoiding the limitations of blockchain sequentially. 

Input and Endorsement Blocks are processed in parallel, utilizing available network resources, while Ranking Blocks are processed sequentially to maintain the blockchain's linearity.

Ouroboros Leios will enable nodes to continuously process multiple tasks. 

Tasks that support parallel processing across nodes are marked green and yellow, and these pertain to Input Blocks and Endorsement Blocks.

This includes the minting and validation of Input Blocks, along with the transactions they contain, which may involve script execution. It also covers the minting and validation of Endorsement Blocks, stake-based voting on these blocks, and the creation of certificates.

Tasks marked in white require sequential processing and are related to Ranking Blocks.

With the implementation of Ouroboros Leios and Peras, Cardano will be utilizing the second generation of the Nakamoto consensus.

text:
The Chang hard fork has introduced on-chain governance to Cardano. 

The community has elected three new members to the interim constitution committee. ADA holders can now delegate their decision-making power to DReps.

Discover #Cardano's governance structure and mechanisms.

Let's first examine how governance functioned during the Shelley era. 

The three founding entities‚ÄîIOG, Cardano Foundation, and Emurgo‚Äîused Genesis keys to approve governance actions. There were seven Genesis keys in total, and any action required the approval of five out of the seven signatures.

During this period, Cardano operated with off-chain governance, meaning $ADA coins were not involved in the decision-making process. Instead, decisions were made solely by the three founding entities.

On-chain governance refers to a system where decisions about a blockchain network are made directly on the blockchain itself. 

This typically involves a voting mechanism where token holders can propose and vote on changes to the network's rules or parameters.

A key aspect is that decision-making power arises from the possession of a scarce resource. For Cardano, this resource is ADA coins. 

The influence of individuals is determined by the number of ADA coins they hold and the coins delegated to them.

ADA withdrawals from the treasury, changing various protocol parameters, and the initiation of a hard fork require a vote.

For each type of governance action, the required approving governance bodies are clearly defined. 

A governance action is approved only if it receives approval from all the governance bodies authorized to vote on it.

For instance, only DReps and Constitution Committee (CC) members vote on ADA withdrawals from the treasury, while SPOs do not participate in this vote.

The new governance structure includes CC members, DReps, and SPOs.

CC members vote on a one-member, one-vote basis.

The CC members include the following entities: 

- Cardano Foundation, 
- IOG, 
- Emurgo, 
- Intersect, 

and three community-elected members: 

- Cardano Atlantic Council, 
- Cardano Japan, and 
- Eastern Cardano Council.

Every year there will be a vote on the new composition of the commission.

After its ratification, the Cardano Constitution will be a fundamental input for the decision-making of CC members.

SPOs vote with the stake delegated to their pools, with most delegations having occurred in the past. This results in each SPO having different voting power based on the stake delegated to their pool.

A new role, DReps, has been introduced. 

DReps must register to obtain a DRep ID, which they then share within the community to request delegations.

This process is similar to the principles used for pools, with similar certificates used to register DReps and delegations.

ADA holders can delegate their ADA to DReps if they prefer not to register themselves.

One stake can be delegated twice. 

For example, 1000 ADAs can be delegated to pool A and further to DRep B. The pool operator and DRep can be different entities or the same entity.

A pool operator can also register as a DRep. In this case, the operator has a stake as an SPO (SPO stake) but must request delegations again from ADA holders in his role as a DRep (DRep stake).

Both SPOs and DReps vote in a one-Lovelace, one-vote style.

It's important to note that the number of governance keys that can be created by registration is unlimited. 

Currently, there are around a few thousand pool operators and several hundred registered DReps.

ADA holders play a crucial role in the decision-making processes through governance bodies. 

Thanks to the fair initial distribution of ADA coins, they likely hold the dominant decision-making power.

It's important to delegate as many ADA coins as possible to DReps to maximize the Active Voting Stake. It is a registered stake that is delegated to DReps or automated No Confidence Drep. 

In short, it is a stake that is ready to vote.

The larger the Active Voting Stake, the more significant and relevant the decisions on governance actions will be.

Don't hesitate to find your DRep and delegate your voting power to them.

Choose responsibly. They hold a significant position in the new governance structure and will shape the future of Cardano.

text:
ADA in the #Cardano treasury is a valuable resource that we must manage responsibly.

While there are frequent suggestions to increase marketing investments, I believe we should do so conservatively.

There are two extreme views on marketing. One is that good products don't need marketing, and the other is that success is only achievable through marketing. I lean more towards the first opinion.

Currently, it's more important for Cardano to invest in building its ecosystem. This includes enhancing scalability, DeFi, ZK cryptography, and improving the user interface. 

Additionally, we need more liquidity, and many people prefer stablecoins like USDC and USDT.

If we create something valuable, users will come. If they stay, money will follow. A strong network effect will attract VC investors.

The presence of users and projects backed by VC funds will generate additional value that people will talk about. Word-of-mouth promotion is free.

Cardano has unique features that make it stand out in the crypto industry. It boasts high decentralization, liquid staking that doesn't require third-party protocols, and native tokens that cannot be frozen by a third party. We also have excellent DEXs and lending platforms. All of this could be marketed.

But would it work?

In the first half of 2024, Polkadot spent $37M on marketing. In January 2024, Polkadot was ranked 12th by market capitalization. It is now 15th.

If we decided to invest $40M in marketing now, we would need approximately 110M ADA from the Cardano treasury. That's roughly a third of the projected revenue for 2025.

Let's learn from the mistakes of others. We cannot afford to spend such huge resources on marketing that may not have the desired effect on the project.

People in the crypto scene are generally aware of Cardano's advantages, but these benefits are often overlooked or misunderstood. 

Another issue is that the media has reported negatively about Cardano until recently, though this seems to be improving.

I don't believe marketing will solve this problem. 

Targeting marketing efforts at crypto communities doesn't make much sense to me. For example, I've seen ads for Polkadot on platform X, but since I'm already familiar with the project, I just ignored them. 

What was your reaction?

I am firmly against proposals that involve paying influencers from the Cardano treasury. I've seen paid influencers merely repost content and make technical analyses. This would be a waste.

On platform X, the best marketing for Cardano is a strong and loyal community. We can win many polls, and every positive article about Cardano gets numerous views and likes. 

Negative articles are filled with disagreeing comments, all thanks to the community's efforts, which come at no cost.

By the way, if you want to get more involved, join the Nexus.

LINK: https://t.co/dVQYbG80Yl

Cardano needs to better showcase its technology. 

Introducing Hydra through playing DOOM was a brilliant idea, generating enthusiastic posts on social media during Rare Evo, and it was relatively inexpensive.

Cardano has more to offer. For instance, the police in Dubai have launched a pilot project using Cardano for criminal investigations. It works fine with the current Cardano scalability.

We need to deliver similar projects and present them smartly.

Direct communication by the Cardano Foundation, IOG, and Emurgo with businesses, banks, and governments is more crucial to the project's success than marketing.

Cardano entities can help them to build great projects. Intersect has a few working groups. Let's support these efforts more.

Present me with an original and interesting marketing idea, and I will support it. 

I would allocate around 5-10M ADA for marketing in 2025. I could consider up to 20M $ADA if presented with a truly unique idea.

Do you agree with me?

text:
I appreciate the effort to attract VCs to Cardano. 

#Cardano's decentralized nature and the advantages of native assets over SC-based tokens, along with its strong security record in DeFi and the benefits of UTxOs over the account-based model, are commendable.

However, for Cardano to be attractive and usable for globally successful projects, it needs:

‚Ä¢  Higher scalability
‚Ä¢  Wallets supporting digital identity
‚Ä¢  ZK cryptography

Currently, Cardano is not ready for mass adoption, but it's important to note that no blockchain meets these prerequisites yet.

No blockchain is currently suitable for projects targeting millions of daily active users, which is why many projects migrate to L2s. While L2s offer scalability, they often compromise on decentralization and security.

Cardano needs to implement Ouroboros Leios, Peras, Hydra (and other L2s like Midgard), and the Partner Chain Framework to be truly ready.

ZK cryptography, which enhances privacy and can significantly improve execution efficiency and scalability, has been delivered with the Chang harp fork, but we are still in the early stages.

Wallets with digital identity are a significant advantage for businesses and Web3, potentially becoming a deciding factor for building on Cardano. We should not underestimate this.

In this context, the 3UtxO initiative seems a bit premature. Let's focus on completing the necessary developments first.

Cardano doesn't need new narratives; it should stay true to its original mission of becoming a global decentralized financial operating system.

However, presenting #Cardano as Bitcoin 2.0 could be a compelling narrative. 

Cardano boasts high decentralization, extended UTxO, enhanced script programmability, on-chain governance, and shorter block times. The next improvement will be related to the Nakamoto consensus.

The Ouroboros Leios and Peras upgrades will be the most significant advancements to the Nakamoto consensus since #Bitcoin's inception.

Like Bitcoin, Cardano has a hard-capped monetary policy. Additionally, thanks to its PoS mechanism, Cardano is more economically sustainable in the long term, eliminating the need for tail inflation.

Cardano will finish what Satoshi started.

text:
There is speculation that Charles left #Cardano after delivering on-chain governance (the Voltaire era) to avoid the complex implementation of scalability solutions like Ouroboros Leios and Peras, which were supposed to be delivered in the Basho era.

The completion of the Basho era would thus be left to the community.

To my knowledge, Charles never explicitly stated that IOG would leave without delivering the Basho era. As far as I know, the team is currently working on Ouroboros Peras.

I believe IOG is going to deliver scalability. In my opinion, IOG should deliver scalability without relying on treasury funding. 

However, I am not aware of @InputOutputHK's official stance on this matter. 

Feel free to share your insight if you know anything. We need to clarify whether scalability will be funded by the treasury or not.

text:
#Cardano, "one Of The Greatest Technical Achievements In Human History" According To  @IOHK_Charles  !

In a constantly evolving ecosystem where projects are multiplying and technologies are competing, few dare to claim to have accomplished one of the greatest technical feats in history. Charles HOSKINSON, the founder of Cardano, made such a statement, placing his project at the pinnacle of global technological achievements. According to him, Cardano is not just another blockchain platform, but a technology comparable to an ‚Äúunstoppable virus‚Äù that spreads inexorably and transforms the crypto industry. This bold assertion comes at a critical moment for Cardano, just after the implementation of the Chang hard fork.

#Cardano : an unprecedented technical feat...

Charles HOSKINSON published a lengthy message on his X account, in which he celebrates ten years of hard work that shaped Cardano. According to him, ‚ÄúCardano has eclipsed Bitcoin.‚Äù He describes his crypto project as ‚Äúone of the greatest technical accomplishments in human history.‚Äù What distinguishes Cardano from other projects, according to HOSKINSON, is its resilience and ability to operate uninterrupted in over a hundred countries. He emphasizes that, despite numerous challenges and criticisms over the years, Cardano has never experienced a downtime. For him, the recent success of the Chang hard fork, adopted by millions of users without any central coordination, demonstrates the robustness and sophistication of the network.

In his remarks, HOSKINSON insists on the unique nature of Cardano. By focusing on these technical aspects, he seeks to position Cardano as an alternative to Bitcoin and a more advanced and mature solution. It is true that the technological successes he claims are based on a solid foundation of academic research and rigorous development, which allows Cardano to stand out in a market saturated with projects often less transparent or less well-structured.

The ‚Äúvirus‚Äù metaphor and its implications for the crypto ecosystem...

Charles HOSKINSON did not just enumerate the technical successes. In his message, he went further by comparing Cardano to a ‚Äúgovernance virus,‚Äù a living, self-replicating, and autonomous entity determined to grow and evolve. This analogy, though provocative, aims to illustrate the resilient and adaptive nature of Cardano in a crypto market often characterized by volatility and uncertainty.

Rather than simply competing with other blockchains, Cardano, according to Hoskinson, positions itself as an ecosystem that evolves organically and adapts to the changing needs of users and markets. Consequently, it is destined for uninterrupted growth.

This rhetoric has garnered both admiration and skepticism on the networks and has drawn streams of comments. While the technological successes of the project are undeniable such as the activation of its Chang update, its bold vision and unique positioning in the crypto ecosystem will continue to fuel the debate on its future place and role in the crypto ecosystem.

Author :  Luc Jos√© A.

#Cardano  $ADA  @Cardano

author.description: crypto content creator | creator @itscattledaddy | #CardanoGirls | $lilybrodi | shefi cohort 13 | not financial advice

quote.text:
One of the deepest lessons I've taken to heart over the past decade is that becoming a public figure means you turn into a human rorschach test where those who don't like you will take any post or comment and assume the worst possible interpretation.  

Working on Cardano this past decade has been a whirlwind of emotions, challenges, and tremendous obstacles to overcome. It's been a journey that not everyone completed, and watching friends fade, false starts, and ending up in a place unexpected, but not undesired, is hard to process. 

I took a drive alone, which I rarely do since getting a security detail, and shared the moment with everyone. It was something I felt appropriate because so many of us went on this journey together and are also feeling so much that it is sometimes hard to express in words. 

It gave me comfort seeing the comments from kindred spirits who got what I was saying. And I suppose I accept how fragile and damaged the other comments are. People in our industry are so used to scams, rug pulls, and evil founders that they can't comprehend an honest ecosystem or the best efforts of so many thousands of people.

It tells me that we have a very long road ahead to heal the damage and avarice. It also tells me a lot about where humanity is. We don't get to have moments to enjoy a pure accomplishment anymore. 

What Cardano has done is one of the greatest technical achievements in human history:

A distributed system that runs in more than 100 countries, which has never shut down, without central coordination just seamlessly upgraded for millions of people who have never met each other to evolve into a decentralized nation complete with its own constitution. The audacity is absurd.

This dwarfs Bitcoin. It's unique, and books will be written about what has happened.  Cardano is now a governance virus that is living, self- replicating, and self-sustaining. It has intelligence and a will to survive and grow. Nothing can shut it down. Nothing can stop its growth. 

Where all of this could go is what I was thinking about while driving. We created something alive together.  Now we all get to live in a world where it exists.

text:
This is it #Cardano peeps. Today is the day! üî•
The Chang hard fork activates Plutus v3 with these capabilities:

Advanced Cryptographic Primitives:
- Support for BLS12-381 curve pairings, enabling efficient zero-knowledge proofs and enhanced security.
- Blake2b-224 hash function for versatile on-chain computations and transaction signature validations.
- Keccak-256 hash function for Ethereum signature verification, enabling cross-chain interoperability.

Improved Performance:
- Introduction of "sums of products" encoding, leading to smaller, cheaper scripts and up to 30% faster execution of smart contracts.

Enhanced Developer Toolkit:
- New bitwise primitives (e.g., integerToByteString, byteStringToInteger) for low-level data manipulation, improving performance and cryptographic operations.

Better Smart Contract Efficiency:
- Optimizations in script size and throughput, reducing costs and improving overall operational efficiency.

Support for Industry Best Practices:
- Enhanced cryptographic capabilities aligned with the latest standards, facilitating smooth migration of smart contracts from other platforms like Ethereum.

Governance Integration:
- Updated script context to support CIP-1694 governance-related entities, enhancing the Cardano ecosystem's governance features.

We are going for number one!

text:
If you are new to #Cardano, here are some X accounts in the Cardano community that you should follow.

1. @IOHK_Charles - Charles Hoskinson, the co-founder of Cardano, provides updates, insights, and his vision for Cardano's future.

2. @cardano_whale - Known for deep dives into Cardano's ecosystem, market analysis, and community engagement.

3. @RichardMcCrackn - Richard McCracken is a prominent Cardano community member, often sharing insights on staking, governance, and Cardano's developments.

4. @cryptorecruitr - Offers content around Cardano's DeFi, staking, and general updates within the ecosystem, often with a focus on opportunities for growth and investment.

5. @JaromirTesar - Provides educational content, often breaking down complex blockchain concepts into understandable insights, particularly useful for newcomers.

6. @ShillMoBaggins - Known for visual technical analysis which can be very insightful for understanding market trends related to Cardano.

7. @conraddit - Shares technical opinions and visions for Cardano's technology and its applications.

8. @StakeWithPride - Offers quality content related to staking, governance, and community initiatives within Cardano.

9. @BeginWallet - For insights into Cardano wallet solutions, which are crucial for managing your $ADA.

10. @MinswapDEX - If you're interested in Cardano's decentralized exchanges, following Minswap will keep you updated on one of the leading DEXs on Cardano.

These accounts cover a range of topics from technical analysis, market trends, educational content, to practical applications like staking and wallet management within the Cardano ecosystem. Following these could provide you with a well-rounded perspective on Cardano's developments, community sentiment, and potential investment opportunities. Remember, while these accounts are influential, always do your own research (DYOR) and consider the broader context of cryptocurrency investments.
